    faqs: [
      { q: "Does 4K really matter for a pet camera?", a: "For most users, 1080p is sufficient. But 4K gives you better digital zoom — you can zoom in on your pet without the image getting pixelated. This is useful if your camera is placed far from your pet's favorite spot, or if you want to check details like whether they actually ate their food." },
      { q: "Do I need to buy an SD card for the xpai?", a: "No — the xpai has 64GB of built-in storage, enough for about 7-10 days of continuous recording at 4K, or 3-4 weeks at 1080p. This is a major cost advantage over cameras that require you to buy a separate SD card ($10-30)." },
      { q: "Can the xpai work as a regular security camera too?", a: "Yes — the xpai works as a general indoor security camera with motion detection, night vision, and two-way audio. The pan/tilt feature and 4K resolution actually make it better than many dedicated security cameras in this price range." },
      { q: "What's the catch at $43?", a: "The app is functional but not as polished as Furbo or Petlibro. The brand is newer, so long-term reliability is less proven. And there's no treat tossing or pet-specific AI features. But for basic monitoring with excellent video quality, these are fair trade-offs at this price point." },
    ],
  },
  "honeytour-robot-camera-review": {
    title: "Honey Tour Movable Pet Camera Robot Review 2026 — A Camera That Follows Your Pet!",
    description: "We review the Honey Tour robot camera — it actually drives around the house to find and follow your pet. 4.7★ rating, no subscription. Is the robot pet cam the future?",
    productId: "honeytour-robot-cam",
    verdict: "The Honey Tour robot camera is the most entertaining pet camera we tested, and it actually works as advertised. It drives around your home on two tank-like treads. Using the app, you can steer it from room to room to find and follow your pet. The 1080p video is clear and the two-way audio lets you talk to your pet through the robot. Traditional pet cameras have a fixed view — if your pet walks out of the room, that's it. The Honey Tour solves this by being able to chase after them. At $160 with a 4.7-star rating across 320 reviews, it's a niche product for a specific type of owner. The limitations are worth noting: no treat tossing, the brand is small with limited support, and cats especially may see the robot as a toy to attack rather than a camera to ignore. It drives best on hard floors and can get stuck on thick carpets or cords. For multi-room homes with curious pets, this is the only camera that can follow your pet around. No other pet camera offers this capability at any price.",
    content: "",
    faqs: [
      { q: "Can the Honey Tour robot actually follow my pet?", a: "Yes — the robot uses motion detection and can be remotely controlled via the app. It drives on two treads that handle hardwood, tile, and low-pile carpet. Cats especially tend to be curious about it (sometimes too curious — expect some batting at the camera). For dogs, it works best when they're calm and not trying to play with it." },
      { q: "Does the Honey Tour robot camera get stuck?", a: "It can get stuck on thick rugs, door thresholds over 1cm, and loose cables. It's best suited for homes with mostly hard floors. The robot is smart enough to avoid walls but not smart enough to navigate complex obstacle courses. Think of it as a remote-control car with a camera, not a Roomba." },
      { q: "Is the 4.7★ rating real with only 300+ reviews?", a: "The rating is high because early adopters love the concept and execution. With only 320 reviews, it's a newer product and the sample size is small. The rating may settle around 4.3-4.5 as more reviews come in. That said, the product delivers on its core promise — a movable camera that follows your pet." },
      { q: "Should I get the Honey Tour robot or a traditional pet camera?", a: "Get the Honey Tour if you have a multi-room home and your pet moves around a lot. Get a traditional camera (Furbo, eufy) if your pet mostly stays in one room. The Honey Tour is complementary — many owners use it alongside a fixed camera for full coverage." },
    ],
  },
  "tractive-gps-review": {
    title: "Tractive GPS Dog LTE Review 2026 — Best Budget GPS Tracker?",
    description: "We tested the Tractive GPS Dog LTE — the most popular budget GPS tracker with 8,900+ reviews. Lives up to the hype, or are there hidden costs you need to know?",
    productId: "tractive-gps",
    verdict: "The Tractive GPS LTE is the best GPS tracker for most dog owners. It balances price, features, and coverage better than any competitor. At $79, it's affordable enough that you won't hesitate to buy one. The global coverage across more than 170 countries means it works whether you're at the neighborhood park or hiking in another country. The virtual fence alerts you about 30 seconds after your dog leaves the safe zone. The activity monitor tracks whether your dog is getting enough daily exercise. It's waterproof enough to survive swimming and rain. The real cost is the subscription: $5 to $13 per month adds up to $60 to $156 per year. Over a typical three-year ownership period, your total cost will be between $259 and $547 depending on your plan. If you hate subscriptions, the $33 No-Fee tracker offers basic tracking without recurring charges. If you need off-grid tracking without cell towers, the $229 Aorkuler is the better tool. For the 90% of dog owners in areas with good cell coverage, the Tractive is the smart choice.",
    content: "",
    faqs: [
      { q: "How long does the Tractive GPS battery last?", a: "2-5 days depending on usage. Live tracking mode drains the battery fastest (about 2 days). Power-saving mode extends it to about 5 days. Recharging takes 2-3 hours via USB." },
      { q: "Does Tractive GPS work without cell service?", a: "It works in 170+ countries using cellular networks (LTE). If you're hiking in an area with no cell coverage, the tracker can't transmit your dog's location. The Aorkuler is a better choice for truly off-grid adventures." },
      { q: "Is the Tractive subscription worth it?", a: "At $5-13/month, it's one of the most affordable GPS subscription plans. The premium plan ($13/month) adds family sharing and extended location history. For most owners, the basic $5/month plan covers what you actually need: live tracking and virtual fence alerts." },
      { q: "How accurate is the Tractive GPS?", a: "Within 2-5 meters outdoors when there's good cell signal. In dense urban areas or heavy tree cover, accuracy drops to 10-20 meters. The virtual fence has about a 30-second delay before alerting you when your dog leaves the zone." },
    ],
  },
  "nofee-gps-tracker-review": {
    title: "No Monthly Fee GPS Dog Tracker Review 2026 — $33 and Done?",
    description: "We review the popular 'No Monthly Fee' GPS tracker — $33 with zero subscriptions. Does this budget option actually work, or do you get what you pay for?",
    productId: "nofee-gps-tracker",
    verdict: "The No Monthly Fee GPS tracker is the ultimate budget pick for owners who refuse to pay subscriptions. It delivers real GPS tracking with zero recurring costs — ever. At $33, it costs less than three months of Tractive's basic plan. If this tracker lasts even one year, you've saved money compared to any subscription alternative. The trade-offs are clear. Build quality is budget plastic, not rugged enough for rough play. Battery life is short at one to two days per charge. The app has occasional bugs and connection issues. Accuracy is five to fifteen meters rather than the two to five meters of premium trackers. For a pet that stays mostly in your yard or neighborhood, these limits are manageable. Think of this as a starter tracker for a new puppy or a backup for a cat that explores a few blocks around your home. If your dog is an escape artist who runs for miles, invest in the more reliable Tractive at $79. If you just want basic peace of mind without another monthly bill, this $33 tracker is a genuine deal.",
    content: "",
    faqs: [
      { q: "Is the No Fee GPS tracker really free after purchase?", a: "Yes — there is genuinely no SIM card to insert, no monthly plan, and no hidden activation fee. The tracker uses a built-in cellular module where the manufacturer covers the data cost. The trade-off is that at $33 with free lifetime service, you're not getting premium build quality or features." },
      { q: "How far does the No Fee GPS tracker work?", a: "It uses cellular networks (like a phone), so it works anywhere there's cell coverage. There's no hard distance limit as long as both the tracker and your phone have cell service. It does NOT work in areas with no cellular signal — this is not a radio-based tracker like the Aorkuler." },
      { q: "How long does the battery last?", a: "About 1-2 days with normal use. This is the biggest weakness — you'll be charging it more often than premium trackers. If you need multi-day battery life, look at the Tractive GPS (2-5 days) or invest in a power bank for on-the-go charging." },
      { q: "Is the No Fee tracker accurate enough?", a: "For the price, yes. Location accuracy is within 5-15 meters — good enough to find which block or park your dog is in, but not precise enough to locate exactly which bush they're hiding behind. The app refreshes every 30-60 seconds, so there's a slight lag." },
    ],
  },
  "aorkuler-gps-review": {
    title: "Aorkuler GPS Dog Tracker Review 2026 — No Phone, No Subscription, No Limits",
    description: "We review the Aorkuler GPS tracker — $229, handheld controller, zero subscription, 3.5-mile range. The ultimate off-grid dog tracker or overkill for most owners?",
    productId: "aorkuler-gps",
    verdict: "The Aorkuler is a niche product that dominates its niche completely. For the right owner — hikers, hunters, rural dog owners — it's the best GPS tracker at any price. What makes it different is the radio frequency system. It does not use cell towers. It does not need a smartphone. It does not charge a monthly fee. The handheld controller shows your dog's direction and distance in real time, like a compass that always points to your pet. The 3.5-mile range in open terrain is impressive for a consumer device. Range drops in dense forest or hilly areas, but the radio signal keeps working where cell phones show zero bars. At $229 upfront, it seems expensive compared to the $79 Tractive. But with no subscription, your total cost after about 18 months is lower than Tractive plus its monthly plan. The controller is bulky, like an old walkie-talkie. The design favors function over style. If you walk your dog in a park with full cell signal, buy the Tractive for $79. If you're deep in the woods with no service and your dog chases a deer, the Aorkuler is the only tracker that will actually help you find them.",
    content: "",
    faqs: [
      { q: "Does the Aorkuler really work without cell service?", a: "Yes — it uses radio frequency (RF) communication between the collar tag and the handheld controller, not cellular networks. This means it works in deep forests, mountains, and anywhere with zero cell signal. The trade-off is limited range (3.5 miles max in open terrain, less in dense areas)." },
      { q: "How accurate is the Aorkuler's direction and distance display?", a: "The handheld controller shows real-time direction (which way your dog is) and distance (how far away in miles/km). Direction accuracy is good to within 10-15 degrees. Distance is accurate to within 50-100 feet. It's not GPS-precise but it's enough to find your dog." },
      { q: "Is the Aorkuler worth $229 vs a $33 no-fee tracker?", a: "For off-grid use, absolutely — the Aorkuler is the only one that works without cell towers. For suburban/city use, the $33 no-fee tracker or $79 Tractive are better value. The Aorkuler is purpose-built for adventurers, not everyday dog walking." },
      { q: "Can I use the Aorkuler on multiple dogs?", a: "Yes, you can pair up to 3 collar tags with one handheld controller. Additional collar tags cost about $100 each. The controller cycles through each dog's location with a button press." },
    ],
  },
  "catlink-young-review": {
    title: "CATLINK Young Pro Review 2026 — Best Multi-Cat Litter Box Under $400?",
    description: "We review the CATLINK Young Pro — $399, multi-cat weight recognition, 13L waste bin. Is this the best value automatic litter box for multi-cat homes?",
    productId: "catlink-young",
    verdict: "The CATLINK Young Pro is the best automatic litter box for multi-cat homes on a budget. At $399, it costs $300 less than the Litter-Robot 4 while still offering per-cat weight recognition that actually works. As long as your cats differ by at least two pounds, the base sensors can tell them apart. The app logs each cat's visits with timestamps and weights. The large 13-liter waste bin handles two cats for five to seven days between changes. The per-cat tracking is the reason to buy this over other budget options. If one cat suddenly changes bathroom frequency, you will catch it days before symptoms become visible. The trade-offs are honest. Build quality is good but not great. The plastic feels lighter than the LR4. Odor control is about 80% as effective with a smaller carbon filter. The app occasionally has awkward translations from Chinese. For two to three cats with different health needs, the CATLINK offers the best value in automatic litter boxes. Single-cat homes should consider the Elspet Pro at $349 instead. You save another $50 and get easier cleaning in exchange for giving up per-cat recognition you don't need.",
    content: "",
    faqs: [
      { q: "How does CATLINK's multi-cat recognition work?", a: "The base has weight sensors that identify which cat is using the box based on their weight. It's accurate for cats with a 2+ lb weight difference. For cats of similar weight, it may confuse them. The app logs each visit with a timestamp and weight reading." },
      { q: "Is CATLINK Young Pro big enough for large cats?", a: "The interior is 22 x 20 inches with a 13L waste bin — adequate for cats up to about 15 lbs. Very large cats (Maine Coons, large Ragdolls) may find it cramped. For extra-large cats, the Litter-Robot 4 or a dedicated large-cat box is a better fit." },
      { q: "How's CATLINK's app experience?", a: "Functional but not polished. You can monitor waste levels, check usage history per cat, and receive alerts. The translations from Chinese to English can be awkward. It gets the job done but isn't as smooth as the Whisker (Litter-Robot) app." },
      { q: "How does CATLINK compare to Litter-Robot 4?", a: "CATLINK wins on price ($399 vs $699) and has per-cat weight ID. Litter-Robot 4 wins on build quality, odor control, app polish, and company reputation. If budget is the priority, go CATLINK. If you want the best experience and can afford it, go Litter-Robot 4." },
    ],
  },
  "elspet-pro-review": {
    title: "Elspet Pro Self-Cleaning Litter Box Review 2026 — The $349 Challenger",
    description: "We review the Elspet Pro — $349, easy disassembly, odor neutralizer. Does this newer brand deliver on quality, or should you stick with established names?",
    productId: "elspet-pro",
    verdict: "The Elspet Pro is the dark horse of the automatic litter box market. It's a newer brand that delivers surprising quality at $349. The standout feature is how easy it is to deep clean compared to every other automatic box we tested. The globe, waste drawer, and litter tray all detach without any tools. Most parts can be rinsed right in the sink. This matters more than you might think. You need to deep clean an automatic litter box every month. A design that fights you during disassembly turns that monthly chore into a real frustration. At $349 with an 18-month warranty — six months longer than most rivals — Elspet is clearly trying to earn customer trust. The app works for basic functions but lacks polish and has occasional connection drops. The brand doesn't have years of user reviews like Litter-Robot or PetSafe. The waste drawer is smaller than the CATLINK's 13-liter bin. For a single-cat home, these trade-offs are minor. You get better cleaning ease and a lower price than the CATLINK Young Pro at $399. If easy maintenance tops your priority list, this is the box to get.",
    content: "",
    faqs: [
      { q: "Is Elspet Pro easy to clean?", a: "Yes — this is its standout feature. The globe, waste drawer, and litter tray all detach without tools. Most parts can be rinsed in a sink or bathtub. Deep cleaning takes about 10-15 minutes, which is faster than most competitors." },
      { q: "How reliable is the Elspet Pro's app?", a: "The app covers basics: waste level monitoring, usage logs, and cleaning cycle control. It occasionally has connection drops that require re-pairing. It's functional but not as reliable as the Litter-Robot or PetSafe apps." },
      { q: "Is the 18-month warranty a sign of confidence or concern?", a: "It's actually above average — most competitors offer 12 months. The longer warranty suggests Elspet is trying to build trust as a newer brand. Just make sure to register your purchase and keep documentation." },
      { q: "Should I buy Elspet Pro or CATLINK Young Pro?", a: "Elspet wins on price ($349 vs $399) and cleaning ease. CATLINK wins on multi-cat recognition (per-cat weight ID) and waste bin size (13L vs Elspet's smaller bin). For single-cat homes, Elspet is better value. For multi-cat homes, CATLINK's per-cat tracking is worth the extra $50." },
    ],
  },
  "wopet-camera-review": {
    title: "WOPET Smart Pet Camera Review 2026 — Best Budget Treat Cam Under $100?",
    description: "We review the WOPET Smart Pet Camera — $99 with treat tossing, two-way audio, and night vision. Is this the best budget alternative to the $179 Furbo 360?",
    productId: "wopet-camera",
    verdict: "The WOPET Smart Pet Camera is the best treat-tossing camera under $100. At $99, you get features that cost $150 to $250 from bigger brands. Treat tossing. Two-way audio. Night vision. Motion alerts. The full interactive experience for roughly half the price. The trade-offs are honest and predictable at this price. There's no pan or tilt — the camera stays fixed where you aim it during setup. The build is budget plastic rather than premium materials. The treat mechanism works about 80% of the time with small round treats but jams on larger pieces. The 1080p daytime video looks good. Night vision is functional if a bit grainy. No subscription is needed for any core features. That's a real advantage over Furbo which charges $5.99 monthly for AI detection. For first-time pet camera buyers who want to try treat interaction without spending $180, this is the obvious starter pick. If you plan to toss treats daily for years, the Furbo 360 at $179 is worth the upgrade.",
    content: "",
    faqs: [
      { q: "Does the WOPET camera's treat tossing actually work?", a: "It works about 80% of the time — which is acceptable at $99 but frustrating if you paid $200+. Small, round treats work best. Large or irregular treats tend to jam. The toss distance is about 3-5 feet, shorter than Furbo's 6 feet. For occasional treat interaction, it's fine. If you plan to use treat tossing daily, save up for the Furbo 360." },
      { q: "Is the WOPET camera's video quality good?", a: "The 1080p video is decent in daylight — clear enough to see your pet's face and what they're doing. Night vision (IR) is functional but grainier than Furbo or eufy. The fixed lens means you can't pan or tilt — point it at the right spot during setup because you can't adjust it remotely." },
      { q: "Does WOPET camera require a subscription?", a: "No subscription required for basic features (live view, treat tossing, motion alerts). Cloud recording requires a plan ($3-5/month). You can use an SD card (up to 128GB) for free local recording. This is generous compared to Furbo which gates AI features behind their $5.99/month plan." },
      { q: "Should I get the WOPET camera or save up for the Furbo 360?", a: "If treat tossing is a must-have and your budget is under $100, get the WOPET. If you want 360° pan/tilt, better build quality, and more reliable treat tossing, save another $80 for the Furbo 360. Or split the difference: get the xpai 4K ($43) for monitoring and skip treat tossing entirely." },
    ],
  },
};

const slug = Astro.params.slug || "litter-robot-4-review";
const review = reviewMap[slug] || reviewMap["litter-robot-4-review"];
const product = allProducts.get(review.productId);
---

<BaseLayout title={review.title} description={review.description} type="article">
  <Breadcrumb crumbs={[{ label: "Reviews", href: "/reviews/" }, { label: product?.name || review.title }]} />

  <article>
    <h1 class="font-display text-3xl font-bold leading-tight text-forest md:text-4xl">{review.title}</h1>

    <div class="mt-3 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-x-5 gap-y-1 text-sm text-bark-muted">
      <span>Updated: <time datetime="2026-05-21">May 21, 2026</time></span>
      <span>10 min read</span>
      <span class="rounded-full bg-sage/70 px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs font-medium text-forest">Advertiser Disclosure</span>
    </div>

    <!-- Product Hero Image -->
    {product?.imageUrl && (
      <div class="mt-6">
        <img src={product.imageUrl} alt={product.name} class="mx-auto h-64 w-full max-w-lg rounded-2xl object-cover shadow-sm bg-sage/60" width="800" height="256" loading="eager" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" />
      </div>
    )}

    <!-- Key Takeaways -->
    <Takeaways items={[
      `Rating: ${"★".repeat(Math.round(product?.rating || 0))}${"☆".repeat(5 - Math.round(product?.rating || 0))} (${(product?.reviewCount || 0).toLocaleString()} reviews)`,
      `Price: $${product?.price || 0}`,
      `Best for: ${(product?.bestFor || []).slice(0, 3).join(" / ")}`,
      `Bottom line: ${(product?.pros || [])[0] || ""}`,
    ]} />

    <!-- Verdict Card -->
    <div class="mt-8 rounded-2xl border border-sage-dark/30 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm md:p-8">
      <p class="font-display text-lg italic text-forest">"{review.verdict}"</p>
      <div class="mt-4 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-4">
        <div>
          <span class="font-display text-3xl font-bold text-forest">${product?.price || 0}</span>
          {product?.price && (
            <p class="text-sm text-bark-muted">About <strong class="text-forest">${Math.round(product.price / 36)}/mo</strong> over 3 years</p>
          )}
        </div>
        <span class="flex items-center gap-1 text-honey text-lg">
          {"★".repeat(Math.round(product?.rating || 0))}
          <span class="text-bark-muted text-sm">({(product?.reviewCount || 0).toLocaleString()} reviews)</span>
        </span>
      </div>
      <a href={product?.amazonUrl || "#"} target="_blank" rel="nofollow sponsored noopener"
         class="mt-5 inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-xl bg-honey px-8 py-3 font-bold text-white shadow-sm transition-all hover:bg-honey-dark hover:shadow-md active:scale-[0.98]">
        Check Price on Amazon
        <svg class="h-4 w-4" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2.5" d="M17 8l4 4m0 0l-4 4m4-4H3"/></svg>
      </a>
    </div>

    <!-- Pros / Cons -->
    <div class="mt-8 grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-2">
      <div class="rounded-2xl border border-green-200 bg-green-50/70 p-6">
        <h2 class="flex items-center gap-2 font-semibold text-green-800">
          <svg class="h-5 w-5" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"/></svg>
          What We Like
        </h2>
        <ul class="mt-3 space-y-1.5 text-sm text-green-800/80">{(product?.pros || []).map((p: string) => <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="shrink-0 font-bold">+</span> {p}</li>)}</ul>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-2xl border border-rose-dark/30 bg-rose-light/50 p-6">
        <h2 class="flex items-center gap-2 font-semibold text-rose-dark/80">
          <svg class="h-5 w-5" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M6 18L18 6M6 6l12 12"/></svg>
          What Could Be Better
        </h2>
        <ul class="mt-3 space-y-1.5 text-sm text-rose-dark/70">{(product?.cons || []).map((c: string) => <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="shrink-0 font-bold">-</span> {c}</li>)}</ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Features -->
    <div class="mt-8">
      <h2 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-forest">Key Features</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 grid gap-2 sm:grid-cols-2">
        {(product?.features || []).map((f: string) => (
          <span class="flex items-center gap-2 rounded-xl border border-sage-dark/30 bg-white px-4 py-2.5 text-sm text-bark">
            <svg class="h-4 w-4 shrink-0 text-honey" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7"/></svg>
            {f}
          </span>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Who Is This For -->
    <div class="mt-8 rounded-2xl border border-sage-dark/30 bg-sage-light/50 p-6">
      <h2 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-forest">Who Is This For?</h2>
      <p class="mt-2 text-bark-muted">{(product?.bestFor || []).join(" / ")}</p>
    </div>

    <FAQ items={review.faqs} />

    <!-- Bottom CTA -->
    {(() => {
      const isLitter = product?.category === "litterBox";
      const isCamera = product?.category === "camera";
      const isGPS = product?.category === "gps";
      const isFeeder = product?.category === "feeder";
      const isFountain = product?.category === "fountain";
      const headline = isLitter ? "Never scoop litter again — for less than 2 coffees a week" :
                       isCamera ? "Stop wondering what your pet is doing when you're away" :
                       isGPS ? "Know exactly where your pet is, any time, anywhere" :
                       isFeeder ? "Never worry about your pet going hungry when you work late" :
                       isFountain ? "The fountain that keeps your pet hydrated and healthy" :
                       `Ready to try the ${product?.name || "product"}?`;
      return (<div class="mt-10 rounded-2xl border border-honey/40 bg-gradient-to-br from-honey/5 to-cream p-6 text-center md:p-8">
      <p class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-forest">{headline}</p>
      <p class="mt-2 text-bark-muted">Get the best price on Amazon with free shipping and returns.</p>
      <a href={product?.amazonUrl || "#"} target="_blank" rel="nofollow sponsored noopener"
         class="mt-5 inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-xl bg-honey px-8 py-3 font-bold text-white shadow-sm transition-all hover:bg-honey-dark hover:shadow-md active:scale-[0.98]">
        Check Price on Amazon
        <svg class="h-4 w-4" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2.5" d="M17 8l4 4m0 0l-4 4m4-4H3"/></svg>
      </a>
      <p class="mt-3 text-xs text-bark-muted/70">As an Amazon Associate, we earn from qualifying purchases. <a href="/affiliate-disclosure/" class="underline">Learn more</a></p>
    </div>)})()}
  </article>

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Review",
    itemReviewed: { "@type": "Product", name: product?.name || review.title, description: review.description, image: product?.imageUrl || "", brand: { "@type": "Brand", name: product?.brand || "" }, offers: { "@type": "Offer", price: String(product?.price || 0), priceCurrency: "USD", availability: "https://schema.org/InStock", url: product?.amazonUrl || "" } },
    author: { "@type": "Person", name: "SmartPetGuide Team" },
    reviewRating: { "@type": "Rating", ratingValue: product?.rating || 4.0, bestRating: 5 },
    datePublished: "2026-05-21",
    publisher: { "@type": "Organization", name: "SmartPetGuide" },
  })} />
</BaseLayout>
